ind us to this world.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; &gt; that is when we look for other learned&#39;s inputs or shastra&#39;s inputs.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; There are too many inputs which say contradictory things. We have to to\n&gt; make some limited use of our intellect as long as we are in this world of\n&gt; duality. Understanding shastra is not easy. At some point, intellect gives\n&gt; way to anubhava, but until then, we have no other choice.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; &gt; On the root of the tree example, I was going with this\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; The example is fine, but it is important to realize that, like all\n&gt; examples, it has limits. Krishna is karma-phala-dAtA, and we have to\n&gt; experience what we, through previous actions, have begged him to let us\n&gt; experience. When we are ready to wholeheartedly accept Krishna with\n&gt; unflinching bhakti, we are made. The reality is that we don&#39;t possess such\n&gt; bhakti, and we are strongly influenced by those around us ... particularly\n&gt; those whom we have RnAnubandha with ... like our forefathers. You can change\n&gt; a lot of things, but changing your DNA is hard. Thus, for the 99.99% of us\n&gt; with less than perfect bhakti, rituals like pitR karma are useful.\n&gt;\n&gt; When you do pitR karma, if you choose to identify strongly with the pitRs,\n&gt; you will go to pitR loka. Similarly with other beings like yakshas,\n&gt; gandharvas etc. But, the point of tarpana is exactly the opposite. Rather\n&gt; than identifying with the pitRs, we are trying to detach ourselves from them\n&gt; and their influences. This will do nothing but help us to cultivate true\n&gt; bhakti and reach our final goal sooner.\n&gt;\n&gt; It is important to understand the intent of the ritual and perform it\n&gt; accordingly.\n&gt;\n&gt; sasneham,\n&gt;\n&gt;    ajit\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; On Sat, Sep 24, 2011 at 7:59 AM, Rama V &lt;vsra_prasad@...&gt; wrote:\n&gt;\n&gt; Namaste.\n&gt;\n&gt; Again every example is taken by the fo