ussing tarpana\n&gt; &gt; (literally &quot;to please&quot;). In the presence of a living father, a better\n&gt; &gt; analogy is that of &quot;going to visit a grandfather who lives elsewhere&quot;.\n&gt; &gt; Certainly, the father should visit the grandfather. Does this mean that\n&gt; the\n&gt; &gt; grandson should not visit the grandfather? And, when it comes to pleasing\n&gt; &gt; the grandfather, is there a monopoly? Most grandparents get a special\n&gt; kind\n&gt; &gt; of a pleasure from their grandkids. All analogies have their limits, but\n&gt; the\n&gt; &gt; CEO analogy, IMO, misses the point.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Pouring water to the roots takes care of the whole of the plant / tree.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; When all other circumstances and factors are conducive to it, merely\n&gt; pouring\n&gt; &gt; water to the roots takes care of the tree. This is not as easy as it\n&gt; &gt; seems. Most trees from India will not survive the cold weather of North\n&gt; &gt; America ... regardless of how much you water it. In advaita, mere gyana\n&gt; is\n&gt; &gt; necessary ... but it takes lifetimes of strenuous karma yoga to reach\n&gt; this\n&gt; &gt; point. Merely reciting a mantra is sufficient ... but it takes lifetimes\n&gt; to\n&gt; &gt; develop the perfect bhakti that must accompany it.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Looks like to each his / her own.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Those who feel strongly can certainly start with the deva and rishi\n&gt; tarpana\n&gt; &gt; :-)\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; sasneham,\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;    ajit\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; On Sat, Sep 24, 2011 at 12:39 AM, Rama V &lt;vsra_prasad@...&gt; wrote:\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Namaste.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; One learned person I know gave an example that an acting CEO or acting\n&gt; &gt; &gt; prime minister does not exist when the real CEO or PM exists. So the\n&gt; &gt; &gt; tarpanam has to be do